The two companies admitted to price fixing, market division and collusive rendering in contravention of the competition act. JOHANNESBURG The Competition Commission says it is optimistic that the five other fire companies implicated in cartel conduct will come forward after two corporations admitted to their participation.On Monday, Fireco Gauteng and Afrion Property Services agreed to pay hundreds of thousands of rands in penalties and to help the commission prosecute remaining members of the Cartel.The two companies admitted to price fixing, market division and collusive rendering in contravention of the Competition Act.The commission s Tshepo Ngwema says: It s about seven companies. Two now have admitted to cartel conduct, they have agreed to pay fine. And also undertaking to assist the commission in prosecuting the others, which is significant because now we ll be able to convict the others because we re assisted by these companies. 